## Memory Leak Analysis: `ScrollTracker`

There are **three compounding bugs** in this component that together cause unbounded listener accumulation.

---

## Bug #1 — Missing Dependency Array (Re-runs on Every Render)

```js
useEffect(() => {
    // ...
}); // ← No [] dependency array!
```

Without a dependency array, React re-runs this `useEffect` after **every single render**. This component updates state on every scroll event (`setScrollY`, `setScrollDirection`, `setLastScrollY`), and every state update triggers a re-render, which triggers the effect again, which attaches **more** event listeners. The progression looks like this:

```
Mount          → 1 scroll listener,  1 resize listener
1st scroll     → re-render → effect runs → 2 scroll listeners,  2 resize listeners
2nd scroll     → re-render → effect runs → 3 scroll listeners,  3 resize listeners
Nth scroll     → re-render → effect runs → N scroll listeners,  N resize listeners
```

By the time a user has scrolled 100 times, there are 100 active scroll handlers all firing simultaneously on every subsequent scroll event.

---

## Bug #2 — No Cleanup Function (Listeners Are Never Removed)

```js
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
    // ← No return () => { removeEventListener(...) }
});
```

A `useEffect` should return a **cleanup function** that runs before the component unmounts (or before the effect re-runs). Without it:

- Navigating **away** from the page does not remove the listeners — they keep running against a detached component in memory.
- The component's closed-over state (`setScrollY`, etc.) keeps the entire component instance alive, preventing garbage collection.
- Every navigation back to the page **mounts a new instance**, attaching another fresh set of listeners on top of the zombie ones from prior visits.

**Lifecycle with both bugs active:**

```
Visit #1: Mount → add listener (total: 1)
         Scroll 50x → add 50 more listeners (total: 51)
Navigate away: nothing cleaned up (total: 51, all still firing)

Visit #2: Mount → add listener (total: 52)
         Scroll 50x → add 50 more listeners (total: 102)
Navigate away: nothing cleaned up (total: 102)

Visit #3: Mount → add listener (total: 103)
...
```

Each zombie instance holds references to its React fiber, state closures, and the DOM — all kept alive by the listeners.

---

## Bug #3 — Anonymous Arrow Functions Are Unremovable

Even if someone tried to add a cleanup, anonymous arrow functions **cannot** be removed:

```js
// Each call to addEventListener creates a brand-new function object
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... }); // reference: 0xAAA1
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... }); // reference: 0xAAA2 — DIFFERENT object!

// removeEventListener requires the EXACT same reference:
window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => { ... }); // reference: 0xAAA3 — no match, NOP
```

`removeEventListener` works by identity comparison (`===`) on the function reference. A new arrow function literal `() => {}` always produces a new object in memory. Without a stable named reference, removal is impossible.

---

## Bug #4 (Bonus) — Stale Closure on `lastScrollY`

Because `lastScrollY` is stored in React state, the scroll handler's closure captures its value at the time the effect ran. Even if cleanup were working correctly with a `[]` dep array, the handler would always compare against `lastScrollY = 0` (the initial value). Using a `useRef` solves this because refs are mutable objects — the handler always reads `.current`, which is the live value.

---

## React 18 Strict Mode: Makes This Visible Early

In development, React 18 Strict Mode **intentionally double-invokes effects**:

```
Mount → run effect → run cleanup → run effect again
```

This simulates unmount/remount to surface exactly this class of bug. With this component, Strict Mode immediately doubles your listener count on first load, making the sluggishness apparent right away in dev without requiring multiple navigations. In production (no Strict Mode), the bug still exists — it just degrades more gradually.

---

## Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // useRef instead of useState: we need the latest value inside the
    // event handler closure without triggering re-renders or stale captures.
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // Named functions give removeEventListener a stable reference to match.
        function handleScroll() {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            // Ref reads are always live — no stale closure problem.
            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up');
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY; // mutate ref directly, no re-render
            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        }

        function handleResize() {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        }

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // Cleanup: runs on unmount (and before re-running if deps change).
        // Same named references → removeEventListener finds and removes them.
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };
    }, []); // Empty array: register once on mount, clean up once on unmount.

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary of All Fixes

| Problem | Root Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Listeners added on every render | Missing `[]` dependency array | Add `[]` — effect runs once on mount |
| Listeners never removed on navigate/unmount | No cleanup function | Return `() => { removeEventListener(...) }` |
| Cleanup couldn't target anonymous functions | New function reference created each call | Extract named functions (`handleScroll`, `handleResize`) |
| Stale `lastScrollY` in handler closure | State read inside a long-lived closure | Move to `useRef` — always reads live `.current` |

